    "summary": "Option B — use our terms throughout, split only for 德",
    "content": "**Option B: use our dictionary terms throughout, including the block quote. The split applies only to 德.**\n\nThe reason 德 gets a split is that the author *redefines* 德 -- the traditional concept (virtue) and the author's concept (constitutive character) are genuinely different things, and the terminological shift enacts the conceptual shift. But the author does NOT redefine 仁, 义, or 礼 in the same way. The author's 现象仁 is not a replacement for 仁 -- it is the phenomenal ground from which 仁 is abstracted. The word 仁 means the same thing in both the Laozi quote and the author's analysis; what changes is the *direction of derivation* (top-down vs. bottom-up), not the meaning of the term.\n\nSplitting 仁/义/礼 between the quote and the analysis would create a false impression that the author is using different concepts, when in fact the author is tracing the *same* concepts to a different origin. The reader needs terminological continuity for 仁/义/礼 to follow the inversion argument -- they must see that the same \"humaneness\" appears in both the classical sequence and the phenomenological reconstruction.\n\nFurthermore, using \"benevolence\" in the quote and \"humaneness\" in the analysis would force the reader to track that these are the same Chinese character, adding cognitive burden for no philosophical payoff. The TN for the block quote can simply note: \"Translation of the Laozi passage follows the conventions used throughout this volume rather than standard sinological renderings.\"\n"
  }
}
